				\begin{document}$$\sigma _{ik}^2$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M10"><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi>σ</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi><mml:mi>k</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn>2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="41467_2019_9639_Article_IEq5.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> values) affect clustering results. The simulated dataset consists of 10 individuals with 400 cells for each. <bold>b</bold> Investigating how different numbers of individuals affect clustering results. We set the level of heterogeneity (mean of <inline-formula id="IEq6"><alternatives><tex-math id="M11">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
